snippet.textDisplay:
I live in Daegu, South Korea, where the country had its first outbreak. EVERYONE wears masks here. EVERYONE. I think that’s one of the big differences with Italy, Iran, and Korea. We all wear masks here. My mom and I wear gloves, as well. Masks help protect the uninfected and help prevent the infected from spreading the virus. When someone who’s not wearing a mask sneezes or spits a little when talking, those droplets are suspended in the air for 30 minutes. Let’s say another person walks into that area within those 30 minutes and is also not wearing a mask, then they breathe in those droplets.

I think the US needs to manufacture and distribute masks asap. Yeah, social distancing helps, but what happens when you’re grocery shopping? People are in and out of supermarkets all the time, I can’t imagine how many droplets are in the air from all those people. Masks, man. Masks.

snippet.textDisplay: FFS, NBC, ventilators don’t function independently, and no number of ventilators are helpful if there is inadequate staffing to care for patients: pets on vents require central lines that need management, catheters for stool and urine, ventilators suctioning, and also need to be shifted in bed every two hours to prevent decubitus ulcers, aka bed sores. Ventilators weaning requires close monitoring, and each patient requires specialty critical care nursing, respiratory therapist care, physical therapy to prevent contractures, nursing assistants to help with patient repositioning, among other things, and physicians, including critical and pulmonary care specialists, and potentially infectious disease specialist, cardiologists if sepsis throws heart patients into failure, GI specialists if stress ulcers develop requiring scoping, nephrologist if sepsis-induced hypotension throws a patient into renal failure... I’m sure I missed at least a few health care specialties...       the point is, while more vents are necessary, they are far from sufficient to keep people alive. There are already high burnout rates among ICU RNs in tertiary and quaternary care facilities, and no amount of hazard pay is enough to ask of them what this report doesn’t even explicitly address.
